It is estimated that tourism to Venice is worth 11billion euros (£9billion) a year, but of all the tourists who visit the city annually, only a quarter stay in a hotel.

Claudio Scarpa, general manager of the Venetian Hotels Association, backed the idea, saying day trippers are a financial burden on the city.

'It is right to find a way to make them pay a kind of entry fee' he says.

The news comes just days after Italy banned large cruise ships from going to Venice amid fears they were destructing the fragile floating city.

